{"id":"1505.01686","submitter":"Detlev Buchholz","authors":"Detlev Buchholz and Rainer Verch","title":"Unruh versus Tolman: On the heat of acceleration","comments":"v3: 11 pages, no figures. Dedicated to the memory of Rudolf Haag.\n  Version as to appear in Gen. Relat. Gravit","journal-ref":"Gen. Relat. Gravit. (2016) 48:32","doi":"10.1007/s10714-016-2029-2","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc hep-th quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is shown that the Unruh effect, i.e. the increase in temperature indicated\nby a uniformly accelerated thermometer in an inertial vacuum state of a quantum\nfield, cannot be interpreted as the result of an exchange of heat with a\nsurrounding gas. Since the vacuum is spatially homogeneous in the accelerated\nsystem its temperature must be zero everywhere as a consequence of Tolman's\nlaw. In fact, the increase of temperature of accelerated thermometers is due to\nsystematic quantum effects induced by the local coupling between the\nthermometer and the vacuum. This coupling inevitably creates excitations of the\nvacuum which transfer energy to the thermometer, gained by the acceleration,\nand thereby affect its readings. The temperature of the vacuum, however,\nremains to be zero for arbitrary accelerations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 7 May 2015 12:47:50 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 14 Oct 2015 21:40:41 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 5 Mar 2016 11:32:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-08"}
